I have completed the task.

I reviewed the `critiques.md` which identified that the current best model (`iter0_candidate0`) struggled most significantly with `length_penalty` — failing to reproduce human preference for longer sequences when the proportion of heads and alternations are controlled for.

To address this, I refined the single underlying mechanism of the subjective prototype hypothesis. Instead of treating the subjective prototype deviation as an average, intensive property (as the original model did), I updated the functional form so that the judgment of randomness evaluates a sequence by *accumulating* its typicality over its length. This simple change allows the model to capture why a short sequence that conforms to the ideal is judged as less random than a long sequence with the exact same rate of deviations, cleanly closing the discrepancy.

